        name='retrieve_information',
        args='{"prompt":"What does the SpaceX S-1 filing disclose about Connectivity revenue? Include all definitions, descriptions, components, and metrics related to Connectivity revenue. Look for both consumer broadband (Starlink) and enterprise/government applications. {{spacex_s1}}"}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'What does the SpaceX S-1 filing disclose about Connectivity revenue? Include all definitions, descriptions, components, and metrics related to Connectivity revenue. Look for both consumer broadband (Starlink) and enterprise/government applications. {{spacex_s1}}'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided SpaceX S-1 filing excerpts, here is a comprehensive breakdown of the disclosures regarding Connectivity revenue, including definitions, descriptions, components, metrics, and financial performance.\n\n### 1. Overview and Definitions\nThe **Connectivity segment** operates a worldwide high-speed, low-latency broadband network powered by thousands of Starlink satellites in Low-Earth Orbit (LEO). It delivers connectivity to millions of consumer, enterprise, and government customers across 156 markets (164 countries, territories, and other markets) as of March 31, 2026. \n\nThe Connectivity business is divided into three main components, plus a mobile-specific offering:\n*   **Starlink Consumer Broadband:** The world’s largest and most advanced space-based internet broadband service, providing fiber-like download speeds globally.\n*   **Enterprise Solutions:** High-speed, low-latency internet services offered to a wide array of enterprises across industries including construction, agriculture, retail, telecom, hospitality, aviation, maritime, and land mobility. \n*   **Government Solutions:** High-speed, resilient connectivity for government customers via Starshield, a secure satellite network designed specifically for government use.\n*   **Starlink Mobile:** Satellite-to-mobile services enabling consumers, businesses, and public-sector customers to use existing phones in more places. *Note: Revenue from Starlink Mobile service offerings is included within the "Enterprise & Government" revenue line item.*\n\n### 2. Revenue Generation Models\nThe Connectivity segment generates revenue primarily through (i) broadband and mobile connectivity services and (ii) the sale of the Starlink Kit (inclusive of the terminal). \n\n**Consumer Broadband Revenue:**\n*   Generated primarily through monthly subscription fees based on geographic market and download speed, plus typically a one-time upfront terminal cost (Starlink Kit).\n*   Broadband contracts are generally month-to-month, and revenue recognized for recurring consumer customers is equal to the amount billed in that month.\n\n**Enterprise Revenue:**\n*   Generated through contracts structured as a combination of subscriptions, data consumption, and capacity, or on a percentage-of-completion basis, depending on customer needs.\n*   Starlink Kit revenue for enterprise customers is recognized upon delivery or installation.\n\n**Government Revenue (Starshield):**\n*   Generated via long-term contracts for Starshield.\n*   Revenue is recognized over time for multi-year contracts using the cost-to-cost input method (recording revenue based on costs incurred to date relative to total estimated cost).\n\n**Starlink Mobile Revenue:**\n*   SpaceX charges Mobile Network Operators (MNOs) either a fixed fee or a per-mobile user fee-based amount, which is typically passed through to the customer via the carrier. \n*   Mobile connectivity agreements are generally multi-year contractual obligations ranging from one to five years, though the customer can generally terminate at any time.\n\n### 3. Revenue Recognition Policies\n*   **Multiple Performance Obligations:** Substantially all contracts with Starlink customers contain multiple performance obligations: (i) broadband services and (ii) the Starlink Kit. The transaction price is allocated to each obligation based on its standalone selling price. Starlink Mobile services have a single performance obligation.\n*   **Service Recognition:** Performance obligations for broadband and mobile services are satisfied over time as the customer simultaneously receives and consumes the benefits. \n*   **Pricing Structures:** Service revenue is generated via (i) fixed-price services requiring advance or recurring monthly payments, or (ii) variable-priced services based on actual data consumption. \n*   **Deferred Revenue:** Advanced payments for broadband and mobile services are included in deferred revenue and recognized either ratably over the subscription term or based on actual data consumption. Deferred revenue primarily relates to Space agreements and Connectivity enterprise/government contracts. Total deferred revenue was $10,179 million as of Dec 31, 2024 (with $4,080M recognized as revenue in 2025), growing to $12,116 million as of Dec 31, 2025.\n\n### 4. Key Operating and Performance Metrics\n**Subscriber Metrics:**\n*   **Starlink Subscribers:** Approximately 10.3 million as of March 31, 2026, up approximately 105% from 5.0 million a year prior. Subscribers are reported on a per-Service Line basis, meaning individual end-users are likely meaningfully higher.\n*   **Starlink Mobile:** Approximately 7.4 million monthly unique devices across approximately 30 countries as of March 31, 2026.\n*   **ARPU (Average Revenue Per User):** Starlink Subscriber ARPU declined 11.2% in 2025 and 22.9% in Q1 2026, primarily due to international expansion and the addition of lower-priced service plans.\n\n**Network and Technology Metrics (as of March 31, 2026):**\n*   **Satellite Constellation:** Approximately 9,600 Starlink broadband and mobile satellites in LEO (~75% of all active maneuverable satellites in orbit). This includes approximately 650 V1 Mobile satellites.\n*   **Service Quality:** Median latency of ~25 milliseconds and median download speeds of 225 Mbps during peak hours for residential users.\n*   **Future Capacity:** V3 satellites (expected 2H 2026) will offer 1 Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite. A single Starship launch can deploy up to 60 V3 satellites, a potential twenty-fold increase in downlink capacity relative to a Falcon 9 launch.\n\n### 5. Cost of Revenue Components\nThe Connectivity segment’s cost of revenue includes:\n*   Depreciation (inclusive of launch, satellite, and ground infrastructure costs)\n*   Starlink Kit costs\n*   Shipping and handling costs\n*   Ground operating expenses\n*   Employee compensation costs (salaries, benefits, share-based compensation for engineering and operations teams)\n*   Payment processor fees\n*   Warranty expense\n*   Inventory excess and obsolescence\n*   Customs and duties\n\n### 6. Financial Performance and Growth Drivers\n**Total Connectivity Revenue Growth:**\n*   **2024:** Revenue increased by $3,730 million compared to 2023, driven by growth in Starlink consumer subscribers and Connectivity enterprise/government sales.\n*   **2025:** Revenue increased by $3,788 million (49.8%) compared to 2024. This was driven by a $2,377 million increase from consumer subscribers (99.9% subscriber growth, offset by 11.2% ARPU decline) and a $1,411 million increase from enterprise and government customers. \n*   **Q1 2026:** Revenue increased by $782 million (31.6%) compared to Q1 2025. Driven by $656 million from consumer subscribers (104.7% subscriber growth, offset by 22.9% ARPU decline) and $126 million from enterprise and government. \n\n**Enterprise & Government Revenue Breakdown (2025 vs 2024):**\n*   Enterprise connectivity business grew by $1,218 million (inclusive of $632 million growth in the mobile connectivity business).\n*   Government connectivity business grew by $193 million.\n\n**Enterprise & Government Revenue Breakdown (Q1 2026 vs Q1 2025):**\n*   Aviation, maritime, and other enterprise business grew by $209 million.\n*   Mobile connectivity business grew by $85 million.\n*   Government connectivity business decreased by $175 million.\n\n**Profitability:**\n*   **Connectivity Income from Operations:** Increased to $4,423 million in 2025 (up $2,417 million from 2024) and $1,188 million in Q1 2026 (up $155 million from Q1 2025). Profitability was offset by higher depreciation of capitalized launch/satellite costs, marketing, and international expansion costs.\n*   **Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA:** Increased to $7,168 million in 2025 (up from $3,849 million in 2024) and $2,087 million in Q1 2026 (up from $1,618 million in Q1 2025).\n\n### 7. Total Addressable Market (TAM)\nSpaceX estimates a total Connectivity market opportunity of **$1.6 trillion**, reflecting primarily consumer use cases. This is broken down into:\n*   **Starlink Broadband:** ~$870 billion opportunity (driven by an estimated 1.8 billion global households in 2025 and 3.3 billion potential end users in currently served markets).\n*   **Starlink Mobile:** ~$740 billion opportunity.\n*   Additional opportunities exist in enterprise and government applications as connectivity evolves into a critical infrastructure layer for autonomous systems, transportation, and smart devices.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=87.229,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
