    tool_call=ToolCall(
        id='call_ccf9de36fbfc41c9b1d25b56',
        call_id=None,
        name='retrieve_information',
        args='{"prompt":"What are the revenue segments disclosed in the SpaceX S-1 filing? Provide details on each segment including Launch, Space Systems, Connectivity, and any other segments. Include segment definitions and revenue figures. {{spacex_s1}}"}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'What are the revenue segments disclosed in the SpaceX S-1 filing? Provide details on each segment including Launch, Space Systems, Connectivity, and any other segments. Include segment definitions and revenue figures. {{spacex_s1}}'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# SpaceX S-1 Revenue Segments\n\nSpaceX discloses **three reportable operating segments** — **Space**, **Connectivity**, and **AI** — with further disaggregation of revenue by type within each segment. Below is a detailed breakdown of each segment, its definition, sub-categories, and revenue figures.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Space Segment\n\n### Definition\nThe Space segment designs, manufactures, and launches reusable rockets (Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, Dragon spacecraft, and the in-development Starship) to provide high-cadence, reliable, and affordable access to space at unprecedented scale. Revenue is derived from fixed-price contracts related to the development and provision of launch services for both commercial customers and governmental agency space programs. The segment flies to LEO, MEO, GEO, lunar, and interplanetary trajectories, as well as the International Space Station.\n\nSpace segment revenue **only reflects customer launches and customer activities**. For launches of SpaceX\'s own Starlink satellites, no inter-segment revenue is recognized; those launch costs are capitalized within the Connectivity segment as property, plant, and equipment.\n\n### Sub-Categories and Revenue Recognition\n\n| Sub-Category | Recognition Method | Contract Duration | Description |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Launch Services** | Point in time (upon launch or deployment of customer\'s payload to intended orbit) | 1–5 years | Fixed-price contracts for commercial and government launch missions. Revenue and costs are deferred until launch/deployment due to interchangeability of flight hardware and minimal unique engineering costs. |\n| **Launch & Development** | Over time (cost-to-cost input method) | 1–14 years | Fixed-price contracts for development of spacecraft and provision of launch and mission services for government agency space programs (utilizing Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, Starship, and Dragon). Performance creates an asset with no alternative use and the Company has an enforceable right to payment. |\n\n### Revenue Figures\n\n| Space Sub-Category | FY 2023 | FY 2024 | FY 2025 | Q1 2025 | Q1 2026 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Launch Services | $1,964M | $2,584M | $2,576M | $566M | $330M |\n| Launch & Development | $1,593M | $1,212M | $1,510M | $299M | $289M |\n| **Space Total** | **$3,557M** | **$3,796M** | **$4,086M** | **$865M** | **$619M** |\n\n### Mix as % of Space Segment Revenue\n\n| | Q1 2026 | FY 2025 | FY 2024 | FY 2023 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Launch Services | 53.3% | 63.0% | 68.2% | 55.2% |\n| Launch & Development | 46.7% | 37.0% | 31.8% | 44.8% |\n\nSpaceX expects Launch & Development to represent a larger portion of Space revenue over time as it continues to serve long-term government contracts. Space revenue growth is expected to remain lower than total company revenue growth as internal businesses (Connectivity and, in the future, AI) absorb most of the growth in launch capacity.\n\n### Segment Profitability (FY 2025)\n- Loss from operations: **$(657) million**\n- Segment Adjusted EBITDA: **$653 million**\n- R&D expense funded for Starship program: **$3,004 million**\n\n### Segment Profitability (Q1 2026)\n- Loss from operations: **$(662) million**\n- Segment Adjusted EBITDA: **$(351) million**\n- R&D expense for Starship: **$930 million**\n\n---\n\n## 2. Connectivity Segment\n\n### Definition\nThe Connectivity segment operates a worldwide high-speed, low-latency broadband data and communications network powered by over 9,600 Starlink broadband and mobile satellites in Low-Earth Orbit, delivering connectivity to millions of consumer, enterprise, and government customers across 164 countries, territories, and other markets. The segment generates revenue from (i) broadband and mobile connectivity services provided through Starlink and (ii) the sale of the Starlink Kit (inclusive of the terminal). **All of the company\'s products revenue is attributable to the Connectivity segment.**\n\nService revenue is recognized over time as the customer simultaneously receives and consumes the benefits. Revenue is generated from fixed-price services (advance or recurring monthly payments) or variable-priced services based on actual data consumption. Advanced payments are recognized either ratably over the subscription term or based on usage.\n\n### Sub-Categories\n\n| Sub-Category | Description |\n|---|---|\n| **Consumer** | Starlink Consumer Broadband — the world\'s largest and most advanced space-based internet broadband service, providing fiber-like download speeds (median of 225 Mbps during peak hours for residential users as of March 31, 2026) with technological capability to provide service everywhere on Earth, including the poles. |\n| **Enterprise & Government** | Enterprise Solutions, Government contracts, and **Starlink Mobile** service offerings (satellite-to-mobile texting and voice services to mobile users). Per footnote (1): *"Enterprise & Government revenue includes revenue from Starlink Mobile service offerings."* |\n\n### Revenue Figures\n\n| Connectivity Sub-Category | FY 2023 | FY 2024 | FY 2025 | Q1 2025 | Q1 2026 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Consumer | $2,817M | $4,830M | $7,208M | $1,492M | $2,148M |\n| Enterprise & Government | $1,052M | $2,769M | $4,179M | $983M | $1,109M |\n| **Connectivity Total** | **$3,869M** | **$7,599M** | **$11,387M** | **$2,475M** | **$3,257M** |\n\n### Segment Profitability (FY 2025)\n- Income from operations: **$4,423 million**\n- Segment Adjusted EBITDA: **$7,168 million**\n- Year-over-year growth: Revenue +49.8%, Income from operations +120.4%, Segment Adjusted EBITDA +86.2%\n\n### Segment Profitability (Q1 2026)\n- Income from operations: **$1,188 million**\n- Segment Adjusted EBITDA: **$2,087 million**\n\n---\n\n## 3. AI Segment\n\n### Definition\nThe AI segment operates a vertically integrated AI platform spanning:\n- **Grok** — a truth-seeking frontier large language model (LLM)\n- **AI solutions for consumer and enterprise customers** — including Grok Business and Grok Enterprise, sold on license-, consumption-, or outcome-based pricing models\n- **X** — a real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform\n- **AI computational infrastructure** — AI hosting and compute capacity\n\nSpaceX plans to prioritize growth and investment in this segment to capture significant opportunities in AI applications and compute infrastructure, and expects to allocate a significant amount of launch capacity to the AI segment in the future.\n\n### Sub-Categories\n\n| Sub-Category | Description |\n|---|---|\n| **Advertising** | Revenue from advertising sales on the X platform. |\n| **AI Solutions & Infrastructure** | Revenue from X subscriptions, data licensing, Grok AI solutions (consumer and enterprise), and AI computational infrastructure services. |\n\n### Revenue Figures\n\n| AI Sub-Category | FY 2023 | FY 2024 | FY 2025 | Q1 2025 | Q1 2026 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Advertising | $2,323M | $1,728M | $1,844M | $443M | $343M |\n| AI Solutions & Infrastructure | $638M | $892M | $1,357M | $284M | $475M |\n| **AI Total** | **$2,961M** | **$2,620M** | **$3,201M** | **$727M** | **$818M** |\n\n### Segment Profitability (FY 2025)\n- Revenue: **$3,201 million**\n- Loss from operations: **$(2,469) million** (referenced in Q1 2026 context; full-year figure implied)\n- Segment Adjusted EBITDA: **$(609) million** (Q1 2026 figure)\n\n### Segment Profitability (Q1 2026)\n- Revenue: **$818 million**\n- Loss from operations: **$(2,469) million**\n- Segment Adjusted EBITDA: **$(609) million**\n\n---\n\n## Total Consolidated Revenue\n\n| | FY 2023 | FY 2024 | FY 2025 | Q1 2025 | Q1 2026 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Total Revenues** | **$10,387M** | **$14,015M** | **$18,674M** | **$4,067M** | **$4,694M** |\n\n### Year-over-Year Revenue Growth Drivers\n\n**FY 2025 vs. FY 2024** — Revenue increased by **$4,659 million (+33.2%)**:\n- Connectivity segment: +$3,788 million (Starlink subscriber base growth + enterprise/government sales)\n- Space segment: +$290 million (increases in Launch and Development)\n\n**FY 2024 vs. FY 2023** — Revenue increased by **$3,628 million (+34.9%)**:\n- Connectivity segment: +$3,730 million (Starlink consumer subscriber growth + enterprise/government sales)\n- Space segment: +$239 million (increase in Falcon 9 launches, partially offset by decrease in Launch & Development due to timing of government contracts)\n- AI segment: −$341 million (decrease in advertising sales, partially offset by increase in X subscriptions and data licensing)\n\n---\n\n## Deferred Revenue\n\nDeferred revenue is recorded when cash payments are received or due in advance of the Company\'s performance. It **primarily relates to Space agreements and Connectivity enterprise and government contracts**.\n\n| Metric | Amount |\n|---|---|\n| Total deferred revenue as of December 31, 2024 | **$10,179 million** |\n| Portion recognized as revenue during FY 2025 | **$4,080 million** |\n| Total deferred revenue as of December 31, 2025 | **$12,116 million** |\n\n---\n\n## Capital Expenditures by Segment\n\n| Segment | FY 2025 | Q1 2026 |\n|---|---|---|\n| Space | $3,832M | $1,052M |\n| Connectivity | $4,178M | $1,332M |\n| AI | *(not disclosed in chunk)* | $7,723M |\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Segment Definitions (from Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements)\n\n> Space Exploration Technologies Corp. and its wholly owned subsidiaries, collectively referred to as the "Company" or "SpaceX," operate three segments – **(i) the Space segment** designs, manufactures, and launches reusable rockets to provide high cadence, reliable, and affordable access to space at unprecedented scale, **(ii) the Connectivity segment** operates a worldwide high-speed, low-latency broadband network powered by thousands of Starlink satellites in Low-Earth Orbit, delivering connectivity to millions of consumer, enterprise, and government customers through our Starlink offering, and **(iii) the AI segment** operates a vertically integrated AI platform spanning a frontier LLM Grok, AI solutions for consumer and enterprise customers, X — a real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform — and AI computational infrastructure.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=56.715,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
