FY 2025 | $81 | −11.2% |\n| FY 2024 | $91 | −8.1% |\n| FY 2023 | $99 | — |\n\n**Definition:** Service revenue generated from Starlink Subscribers during the period ÷ (average number of Starlink Subscribers during the period × number of months in the period).\n\n**Trend & Outlook:**\n- ARPU has declined every year since 2023, driven primarily by **international expansion** and the **addition of lower-priced service plans**.\n- The company explicitly states its strategy is focused on **driving sustainable revenue growth and expanding margins through operational efficiencies and technological advancements, rather than prioritizing increases in ARPU**.\n- ARPU is **expected to continue declining** over the next few years as:\n  - The portion of the subscriber base outside North America grows.\n  - Lower-priced service plans are added.\n  - Monthly service plan fees for broadband offerings are adjusted.\n- These declines are expected to be **offset by increased scale** and technological advancement in launch, satellite, and user terminal operations.\n\n### Starlink Mobile ARPU (Assumptions, Not Actuals)\nThe company discloses **region-specific ARPU assumptions** (not actual reported figures) for market sizing purposes:\n\n| Market Tier | Weighted Avg. Monthly Mobile ARPU |\n|---|---|\n| High-income markets | $18 |\n| Upper-middle income markets | $5 |\n| Lower-middle income markets | $2 |\n| Low-income markets | $2 |\n| **Global weighted average** | **$8** |\n\nBased on these assumptions, the estimated Starlink Mobile market opportunity is **$740 billion**.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Satellite & Network Operating Metrics\n\n### Satellite Constellation\n- **~9,600 Starlink broadband and mobile satellites** in LEO as of March 31, 2026.\n- This represents **~75% of all active maneuverable satellites in orbit**.\n- **V1 Mobile constellation:** ~650 V1 Mobile satellites dedicated to satellite-to-mobile capabilities (began deploying January 2024).\n- **V3 next-generation satellites:** Designed to offer **1 Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite**; deployment expected to commence in H2 2026 using Starship. A single Starship launch can deploy up to **60 V3 satellites**, representing a potential **twenty-fold increase** in downlink capacity deployed relative to a Falcon 9 launch.\n\n### Broadband Performance\n- **Median latency:** ~25 milliseconds as of March 31, 2026.\n- **Median download speed:** 225 Mbps during peak hours for residential users as of March 31, 2026.\n- Technological capability to provide service everywhere on Earth, including the poles.\n\n### Geographic Coverage\n- **164 countries, territories, and other markets** for broadband.\n- Collectively home to **more than 3.3 billion people**.\n- Starlink Mobile available across **~30 countries**.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Segment Financial Metrics\n\n### Segment Income from Operations\n| Period | Income from Operations ($M) |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | $1,188 |\n| Q1 2025 | $1,033 |\n| FY 2025 | $4,423 |\n| FY 2024 | $2,006 |\n| FY 2023 | $469 |\n\n### Segment Adjusted EBITDA\n| Period | Adjusted EBITDA ($M) |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | $2,087 |\n| Q1 2025 | $1,618 |\n| FY 2025 | $7,168 |\n| FY 2024 | $3,849 |\n| FY 2023 | $1,602 |\n\n---\n\n## 5. Revenue Breakdown (from MD&A Narrative)\n\n### Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025\n- Total revenue increased **$782 million (31.6%)**.\n- **Consumer subscriber revenue:** +$656 million (driven by 104.7% subscriber growth, offset by 22.9% ARPU decline).\n- **Enterprise & government revenue:** +$126 million:\n  - Aviation, maritime, and other enterprise: +$209 million\n  - Mobile connectivity: +$85 million\n  - Government connectivity: −$175 million\n\n### FY 2025 vs. FY 2024\n- Total revenue increased **$3,788 million (49.8%)**.\n- **Consumer subscriber revenue:** +$2,377 million (99.9% subscriber growth, offset by 11.2% ARPU decline).\n- **Enterprise & government revenue:** +$1,411 million:\n  - Enterprise connectivity: +$1,218 million (including mobile connectivity +$632 million)\n  - Government connectivity: +$193 million\n\n### FY 2024 vs. FY 2023\n- Total revenue increased **$3,730 million (96.4%)**.\n- **Consumer subscriber revenue:** +$2,013 million (96.5% subscriber growth, offset by 8.1% ARPU decline).\n- **Enterprise & government revenue:** +$1,717 million:\n  - Enterprise connectivity: +$466 million\n  - Government connectivity: +$1,250 million\n\n---\n\n## 6. Cost & Expense Drivers (Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025)\n\n### Cost of Revenue: +$437 million (36.0%)\n| Driver | Amount ($M) |\n|---|---|\n| Higher depreciation (capitalized launch & satellite costs) | $276 |\n| Ground operating costs | $50 |\n| Customer support and installation costs | $42 |\n| Payment processor fees | $19 |\n| Freight costs | $15 |\n| Warranty costs | $12 |\n\n### R&D: +$82 million (66.7%)\n| Driver | Amount ($M) |\n|---|---|\n| Next-generation satellite production development | $62 |\n| Starlink Kits development | $8 |\n| Ground equipment development | (additional) |\n\n---\n\n## 7. Enterprise Customer Retention\n- Since 2023, **no Starlink Enterprise customer contributing more than $750,000 of annual revenue has voluntarily discontinued service**, despite the ability to cancel at any time.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Revenue Model Summary\n| Customer Type | Revenue Model |\n|---|---|\n| Consumer | Monthly subscription fees (based on geography and speed) + one-time Starlink Kit sale; revenue recognized ratably over service period |\n| Enterprise | Combination of subscriptions, data consumption, and capacity contracts; recognized over time or on percentage-of-completion basis |\n| Government | Long-term contracts for Starshield (secure, dedicated satellite network for U.S. Government and national security) |\n| MNOs (Mobile) | Fixed fee or per-mobile user fee-based amount, typically passed through to customer via carrier |\n\n---\n\n## Metrics NOT Disclosed\n\nThe following metrics are **not disclosed** for the Connectivity segment:\n\n### Subscriber-Level Metrics\n- **Churn rate** (gross or net)\n- **Customer acquisition cost (CAC)**\n- **Subscriber lifetime value (LTV)**\n- **Net subscriber additions** (only period-end counts and YoY growth percentages are provided)\n- **ARPU by service plan type** (Residential vs. Roam vs. Business Priority — not broken out)\n- **ARPU by geography** (actual figures — only mobile ARPU *assumptions* are provided for market sizing)\n- **Average revenue per subscriber by cohort or tenure**\n- **Contribution margin per subscriber**\n- **Data consumption per subscriber**\n- **Average bandwidth usage per subscriber**\n\n### Hardware/Kit Metrics\n- **Starlink Kit shipment volumes** (number of terminals shipped/delivered)\n- **Starlink Kit average selling price (ASP)**\n- **Kit sales revenue** (not separated from service revenue as a KPI)\n- **Kit cost of goods sold or gross margin**\n- **Terminal manufacturing cost**\n\n### Network/Capacity Metrics\n- **Network capacity utilization** (total available capacity vs. used capacity)\n- **Total network throughput** (aggregate data delivered)\n- **Ground station/gateway count**\n- **Number of gateways or points of presence**\n- **Satellite manufacturing cost per unit**\n- **Launch cost per satellite deployed**\n- **Actual satellite power consumption or utilization**\n\n### Enterprise/Government Metrics\n- **Number of enterprise customers** (total count not disclosed)\n- **Number of government customers** (total count not disclosed)\n- **Enterprise/government revenue as a discrete line item** (only discussed narratively within MD&A)\n- **Starlink Mobile revenue** (not broken out separately from total Connectivity revenue)\n- **Starshield revenue** (not separately disclosed)\n- **Average contract value** for enterprise or government customers\n- **Revenue retention rate** (net or gross dollar retention)\n\n### Financial Metrics\n- **Segment gross margin** (not explicitly disclosed as a percentage)\n- **Segment operating margin** (can be derived from income from operations ÷ revenue, but revenue is not given as a discrete line item in the segment table)\n- **Capital expenditures** allocated to the Connectivity segment\n- **Depreciation expense** as a standalone line (only discussed as a driver within cost of revenue narrative)\n- **Stock-based compensation** allocated to the Connectivity segment\n\n### Operational Metrics\n- **Number of countries with active Starlink Mobile service** vs. total countries served (only ~30 countries mentioned for mobile, 164 for broadband)\n- **Number of retail stores** carrying Starlink (described as "thousands" but not quantified)\n- **Marketing spend** for the Connectivity segment (not separately disclosed)\n- **Employee headcount** allocated to the Connectivity segment',
