        output='# Connectivity Revenue Breakdown and Deferred Revenue Analysis\n\n## 1. Service vs. Products Revenue Breakdown\n\nThe filing explicitly states: **"All of products revenue is attributable to the Connectivity segment."** This means the company-wide products/services disaggregation can be used to derive the Connectivity split:\n\n**Three Months Ended March 31, 2026:**\n| Component | Amount ($M) |\n|---|---|\n| Products (Starlink Kit sales) | $380 |\n| Services (broadband, mobile, enterprise/government) | $2,877 |\n| **Total Connectivity** | **$3,257** |\n\n**Three Months Ended March 31, 2025:**\n| Component | Amount ($M) |\n|---|---|\n| Products (Starlink Kit sales) | $352 |\n| Services (broadband, mobile, enterprise/government) | $2,123 |\n| **Total Connectivity** | **$2,475** |\n\n*(Services figures derived as: Total Connectivity revenue minus Products revenue, since all products revenue flows through Connectivity.)*\n\nFor the full year 2025, total Connectivity revenue was **$11,387 million** (vs. $7,599 million in 2024 and $3,869 million in 2023), though the annual products/services split is not separately tabulated in the excerpts provided.\n\nWithin the Services category, the filing further disaggregates Connectivity revenue by customer type:\n\n| Connectivity Sub-segment | FY 2025 ($M) | FY 2024 ($M) | FY 2023 ($M) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Consumer | 7,208 | 4,830 | 2,817 |\n| Enterprise & Government (incl. Starlink Mobile) | 4,179 | 2,769 | 1,052 |\n| **Total Connectivity** | **11,387** | **7,599** | **3,869** |\n\n---\n\n## 2. Geographic Revenue Breakdown\n\n**No specific geographic revenue breakdown is disclosed** in the provided excerpts. The filing references that Connectivity services are delivered "throughout 156 markets" and discusses ARPU declines "primarily due to international expansion and the addition of lower priced service plans," but it does not present a quantitative revenue disaggregation by geography (e.g., domestic vs. international, or by region). The only geographic color provided is qualitative:\n\n- Starlink Subscriber ARPU declined **11.2%** in FY 2025 and **22.9%** in Q1 2026, attributed to international expansion into lower-priced markets.\n- Starlink Mobile partnerships span "approximately 30 MNOs on six continents, covering an area that is home to approximately 1.9 billion people."\n\n---\n\n## 3. Deferred Revenue Related to Connectivity\n\nThe filing does **not** disclose a standalone dollar figure for deferred revenue attributable solely to Connectivity. Instead, it states that deferred revenue **"primarily relates to Space agreements and Connectivity enterprise and government contracts"** — bundling the two segments together without separate quantification.\n\nThe aggregate deferred revenue balances disclosed are:\n\n| Date | Total Deferred Revenue ($M) | Amount Recognized as Revenue |\n|---|---|---|\n| December 31, 2024 | $10,179 | $4,080 recognized during FY 2025 |\n| December 31, 2025 | $12,116 | $1,165 recognized during Q1 2026 |\n| March 31, 2026 | $13,236 | — |\n\nThe filing clarifies that the Connectivity-related portion of deferred revenue arises specifically from **Connectivity enterprise and government contracts** (not consumer broadband), because:\n\n- Consumer broadband contracts are "generally month-to-month" with revenue recognized equal to the amount billed each month, limiting advance-payment deferrals.\n- Mobile connectivity agreements are "generally multi-year contractual obligations that range from one to five years," generating more significant deferred revenue.\n- Starshield (government) contracts use the cost-to-cost input method over multi-year periods, contributing to deferred revenue.\n- Starlink Kit (product) revenue is recognized at a point in time upon delivery/installation, so it does **not** generate deferred revenue.\n\nThe broader backlog of **$27,621 million** as of March 31, 2026 (of which $13,236 million was recognized as deferred revenue) provides additional context, with approximately 36% expected to be recognized within one year, 46% between one and three years, and 18% thereafter — but again, no Connectivity-specific carve-out is provided within these figures.',
